{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=o|かい}}
From {{der|ja|ltc|sort=かい|-}} {{ltc-l|界|boundary}}.

In Buddhist contexts, derived from the {{cog|ltc|-}} term used as a translation of {{der|ja|sa|sort=かい|धातु||layer, stratum}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|さかい}}

{{IPAchar|/sakapi/}} → {{IPAchar|/sakaɸi/}} → {{IPAchar|/sakahi/}} → {{IPAchar|/sakai/}}

The {{m|ja|連用形|tr=ren'yōkei||continuative or stem form}} of obsolete verb {{m|ja|境う|tr=sakau||to divide, to form a boundary between things}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref>

Some sources<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref> further derive the verb as {{der|ja|ojp|sort=さかい|-}} element {{m|ja|境|tr=saka||division, border, boundary}} + auxiliary verb {{m|ja|ふ|tr=fu}} indicating repetition or ongoing state. However, given the semantics, this could also be analyzed as the repetitive or ongoing aspect of {{der|ja|ojp|sort=さかい|-}}-derived verb ''saku'' with an underlying meaning of “to split apart, to separate, to put distance between”, spelled variously as {{m|ja|割く}}, {{m|ja|裂く}}, {{m|ja|離く}}, or {{m|ja|放く}}, and cognate with {{m|ja|咲く|tr=saku||to bloom|pos=from the idea of the blooms splitting open}}, {{m|ja|栄える|tr=sakaeru||to prosper|pos=extended from the ''bloom'' sense}}, {{m|ja|盛ん|tr=sakan||prospering, fluorishing}}.
